<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">High water</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you run a hedge fund and get 20% of=
 the profits, that motivates you to make a lot of profits. Your investors w=
ant that; they want you to be motivated. If, one year, you lose money and a=
re down 5%, the way most hedge funds work is that you have to earn back tha=
t 5% =E2=80=94=C2=A0you have to get back to the previous high-water mark =
=E2=80=94 before taking a cut of the profits. If, the next year, you are up=
 4%, you will not take a cut of that 4% profit, because you are still below=
 the high-water mark. If instead you earn 30%, you will take your 0% of the=
 profits back to the high-water mark and 20% of the profits above it.</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Your investors like this high-water mechanism be=
cause:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin=
: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">They would resent paying yo=
u a cut of the =E2=80=9Cprofits=E2=80=9D when they have actually lost money=
 themselves; they only want you to take a cut of <em>actual </em>profits.</=
li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This setup motivates you not to los=
e money in the first place.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This only=
 goes so far, though. If you lose 39% one year and 21% the next, then in th=
e=C2=A0<em>third=C2=A0</em>year you need to make a return of 108% to get ba=
ck to even and start getting paid any performance fees at all.[6] That is h=
ard to do! Or you could make 30% returns for your investors for the next th=
ree years without getting paid,[7] which is unpleasant. On the one hand, ye=
ah: You lost all that money for your investors, it is only fair that you sh=
ould work for them for free for a few years to make it up to them. On the o=
ther hand, your motivation is going to suffer if making way-above-market re=
turns for years on end still won=E2=80=99t earn you a bonus. Given the high=
-water mark, you might give up, fire your analysts, park everything in inde=
x funds and live off the fixed management fee. Or=C2=A0more realistically y=
ou might quit, close your fund=C2=A0and go get a job at someone else=E2=80=
=99s hedge fund where you can earn a bonus this year.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Obviously one possibility is that you <em>should=C2=A0</em>quit,=
 because you repeatedly lost all that money for your investors. The investo=
rs might think that! They might pull their remaining money, after you lost =
so much of it. But if they=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>pull their mone=
y =E2=80=94=C2=A0if they conclude that you are a good investor who can stil=
l do good things for them, and you just had two unfortunate=C2=A0years =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0then really they will have to renegotiate your high-water mark.=
 If they want you to keep working for them =E2=80=94=C2=A0again, a weird ch=
oice, but a possible one =E2=80=94=C2=A0they will have to incentivize you t=
o do so. Which means that if you go from down 50% to down 30% they gotta pa=
y you, even if they resent it.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So <a =
href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27445764.287600/aHR0c=
HM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDQtMjEvcGxvdGtpbi1z=
LW1lbHZpbi1jYXBpdGFsLXJlYm9vdHMtYWZ0ZXItY3J1c2hpbmctc3RyaW5nLW9mLWxvc3Nlcz9=
jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDIxMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bm=
V3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA0MjEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cB91cb6f94" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> how=E2=80=99s Gabe Plotkin doing</a>?</p=
><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gabe Plotkin=E2=80=99s Melvin Cap=
ital is looking to reboot after losing more than half its assets under mana=
gement since the start of 2021.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Plotk=
in, 43, is changing the firm=E2=80=99s terms, most importantly requiring an=
yone who wants to stay in the fund to start paying performance fees again e=
ven though their investments are underwater. Previously, Plotkin would have=
 had to recoup his losses -- in this case deliver a return of more than 100=
% -- before charging those fees. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=
As of June 1, performance fees will drop to a range of 15% to 25%, and will=
 revert to the current level of 20% to 30% on Jan. 1, 2025.=C2=A0 ...</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Plotkin is hoping investors will stick with him =
despite a 39% plunge last year, fueled by a Reddit-fueled short-squeeze tha=
t January, and a 21% decline in the first quarter of 2022. Melvin still man=
aged to attract new money, even though returns later in 2021 weren=E2=80=99=
