802" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> making the companies pay for them</a>:</p><blockquote><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Uber Technologies Inc.=E2=80=99s insistence on arbitr=
ating customer disputes may have backfired in the face of a conservative ca=
mpaign challenging the company=E2=80=99s move to boost Black-owned business=
es after George Floyd=E2=80=99s murder.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The=
 firm of William Consovoy, a lawyer best-known for representing former Pres=
ident Donald Trump, used social media to enlist customers who claimed Uber =
Eats=E2=80=99s 2020 waiver of delivery fees for Black-owned restaurants con=
stituted =E2=80=9Cunlawful reverse discrimination=E2=80=9D against those or=
dering from other businesses and ultimately filed more than 31,000 individu=
al demands for arbitration.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last week, a Ne=
w York appeals court ruled that Uber had to pay the American Arbitration As=
sociation an invoice of nearly $11 million to deal with the Consovoy firm=
=E2=80=99s claims. The total is expected to top $91 million in fees alone, =
an amount Uber called =E2=80=9Castronomical.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">But the court said in its Thursday ruling that Uber was bound by=
 its own bargain.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWhile Uber=
 is trying to avoid paying the arbitration fees associated with 31,000 near=
ly identical cases, it made the business decision to preclude class, collec=
tive, or representative claims in its arbitration agreement with consumers =
and AAA=E2=80=99s fees are directly attributable to those decisions,=E2=80=
=9D the court said.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Arbitration is ge=
nerally seen as more business-friendly than litigation, and Uber has aggres=
sively defended its right to require customers and workers to arbitrate dis=
putes instead of filing lawsuits.=C2=A0 =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">According to the decision, Uber=E2=80=99s deal with the AAA calls fo=
r the company to pay a $500 filling fee, $1,400 standard case management fe=
e, $1,500 arbitrator fee for each matter. Though AAA had discounted the fil=
ing fees, Uber claimed the amount sought was still nearly 75% of the associ=
ation=E2=80=99s total 2020 operating revenue.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Yeah, I=E2=80=99m sorry, without endorsing the specific cla=
im here I have to say that this is good trolling. Also I have to say that i=
f I worked for AAA I=E2=80=99d be quietly trying to sign up more lawyers to=
 do this. For the lawyer=C2=A0and the plaintiffs, this is just trolling. Fo=
r the AAA it=E2=80=99s 75% of its budget!=C2=A0</p><table class=3D"header" =
